<file path=".github/workflows/windows-ci.yml">
name: Windows CI

on:
  workflow_dispatch:
    inputs:
      smoke_command:
        description: "Optional custom command to start the app for the readiness probe"
        required: false
        default: ""
      run_package:
        description: "Also build the Windows installer (NSIS)"
        type: boolean
        default: true
  push:
    branches: [master]
    paths:
      - "src/**"
      - "electron/**"
      - "python/**"
      - "sandbox/**"
      - "scripts/**"
      - "package.json"
      - "package-lock.json"
      - "requirements.txt"
      - ".github/workflows/windows-ci.yml"
      - ".github/workflows/_reusable-windows-build.yml"
  pull_request:
    branches: [master]

jobs:
  windows-smoke:
    runs-on: windows-latest
    timeout-minutes: 20
    env:
      OPENROUTER_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.OPENROUTER_API_KEY }}
      OPENROUTER_BASE_URL: https://openrouter.ai/api/v1
      OPENAI_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.OPENROUTER_API_KEY }}
      OPENAI_BASE_URL: https://openrouter.ai/api/v1
      MODEL_NAME: deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash
      AI_MODEL: deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash
      LLM_MODEL: deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash
      CI: "true"
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          persist-credentials: false

      - name: Validate electron main syntax (fail fast)
        shell: pwsh
        run: node --check electron/main.mjs

      - name: Setup Node
        uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: 22
          cache: npm

      - name: Verify required secrets present
        shell: pwsh
        run: |
          if (-not $env:OPENROUTER_API_KEY) {
            Write-Error "Missing secret OPENROUTER_API_KEY"
            exit 1
          }
          Write-Host "Secrets check: OK"

      - name: Install dependencies
        shell: pwsh
        run: npm ci

      - name: Setup Python
        uses: actions/setup-python@v5
        with:
          python-version: "3.11"

      - name: Install Python deps for executor build
        shell: pwsh
        run: |
          python -m pip install --upgrade pip
          pip install -r requirements.txt

      - name: Build Python executor
        shell: pwsh
        run: npm run build:executor:win

      - name: OpenRouter connectivity probe
        shell: pwsh
        run: node scripts/smoke-openrouter.mjs

      - name: Datasets parser smoke (datasets.txt)
        shell: pwsh
        run: npx tsx scripts/smoke-datasets.ts

      - name: Build
        shell: pwsh
        run: npm run build

      - name: Test
        shell: pwsh
        run: npm test

      - name: HTTP readiness probe (next start)
        shell: pwsh
        run: node scripts/smoke-http.mjs
        env:
          SMOKE_START_COMMAND: ${{ github.event.inputs.smoke_command }}

      - name: Upload smoke logs
        if: always()
        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: windows-smoke-logs
          path: |
            windows-smoke.log
            *.log
          if-no-files-found: ignore

  windows-package:
    if: ${{ github.event_name != 'workflow_dispatch' || github.event.inputs.run_package == 'true' }}
    uses: ./.github/workflows/_reusable-windows-build.yml
    with:
      artifact_name: windows-installer
      publish_release: false
</file>

<file path="docs/decisions/0007-improvement-proposal-rules.md">
# 0007 Improvement Proposal Rules

Date: 2026-06-04

## Status

Accepted

## Context

Phase 5 adds `harness-cli propose`, which changes the harness evolution model.
The command must be useful without becoming an unchecked source of scope creep
or circular recommendations.

## Decision

Improvement proposals are advisory, rule-based, and evidence-backed. The command
may summarize repeated friction, repeated interventions, and audit drift. It may
create `proposed` backlog items only when `--commit` is supplied.

Every proposal must include:

- affected Harness component,
- concrete evidence,
- predicted impact,
- risk lane,
- suggested action,
- validation plan,
- confidence level.

High-risk proposal implementation still requires human review and a durable
decision record when it changes source hierarchy, architecture direction,
validation requirements, or risk policy.

## Alternatives Considered

1. Generate free-form LLM recommendations. Rejected because Phase 5 needs a
   deterministic and auditable evolution role.
2. Automatically apply proposed changes. Rejected because the harness must not
   rewrite its own policy without review.
3. Only report audit findings. Rejected because H5 requires proposed
   improvements, not just drift detection.

## Consequences

Positive:

- Repeated operational patterns can become backlog items.
- Proposal output is explainable and testable.
- Human review remains the gate for risky harness changes.

Tradeoffs:

- Rule-based grouping can miss semantically similar phrasing.
- Audit-based proposals may be housekeeping rather than strategic evolution.

## Follow-Up

- Use benchmark runs and closed backlog outcomes to improve proposal quality in
  later phases.
</file>

